; ABNF (RFC 5234) grammar for the animation.cfg and animevents.cfg text
; formats, derived from BG_ParseAnimationFile / BG_ParseAnimationEvtFile /
; ParseAnimationEvtBlock and the shared COM_Parse/COM_ParseExt tokenizer in
; reference/ja_animation_parse.c.
;
; Scope and assumptions:
;   - This grammar is meant to be lossless: a parser built from it needs to
;     round-trip a file byte-for-byte (comments, exact inter-token
;     whitespace, and any tolerated stray content all have to survive a
;     read-then-write cycle unchanged). That's why every "the original
;     engine doesn't recognize this" case below is modeled as its own
;     bounded grammar alternative, rather than being waved off as an error
;     path outside the grammar. Capturing the *contents* of `sep` (and of
;     each `token`) verbatim for reproduction is the job of the parser we
;     build from this spec, not something that changes the grammar's shape.
;   - Table-size limits (MAX_ANIMATIONS, MAX_ANIM_EVENTS, MAX_TOKEN_CHARS,
;     etc.) are the engine's own runtime array bounds, not part of the file
;     format, and are intentionally left out — mods rebuild with different
;     limits.
;   - Identifiers (anim names, event-type names, channel/footstep names,
;     "include"/"UPPEREVENTS"/"LOWEREVENTS") are matched case-insensitively
;     throughout the source (Q_stricmp/Q_stricmpn). RFC 5234 §2.3 already
;     makes quoted-string terminals case-insensitive by default, so this
;     needs no extra grammar machinery.
;   - Core rules DIGIT and DQUOTE used per RFC 5234 Appendix B.1.

; === Shared tokenizer (COM_Parse / COM_ParseExt) ===
;
; Every field in both file formats is one whitespace/comment-delimited
; token. COM_Parse always allows line breaks within its token stream, so
; records aren't line-based - whitespace and comments are freely
; interchangeable separators wherever a token boundary is expected.

sep           = 1*(ws-char / line-comment / block-comment)
ws-char       = %x01-20
                ; whatever SkipWhitespace treats as whitespace: any byte
                ; from 0x01 to 0x20 inclusive, not just the four values
                ; RFC 5234's WSP/CR/LF core rules cover - e.g. vertical tab
                ; and form feed count too. A literal NUL (0x00) is handled
                ; separately by SkipWhitespace as true end of file, not a
                ; skippable separator.
line-comment  = "//" *(%x00-09 / %x0B-10FFFF)
                ; runs to the next LF, or to end of file if there isn't one
block-comment = "/*" comment-body ["*/"]
                ; matches up to (and excludes) the first "*/"; if none is
                ; found, the comment - and therefore the file - simply ends
                ; there, same as an unterminated quoted-token
comment-body  = *(non-star / (1*"*" not-slash)) *"*"
                ; "a string not containing '*/' as a substring", the usual
                ; construction for excluding a multi-character delimiter
                ; from free-form content whose own characters ('*') can
                ; still appear singly within it - a plain *(%x00-10FFFF)
                ; wouldn't pin down "first occurrence" on its own, since
                ; ABNF repetition has no inherent greedy/lazy behavior; this
                ; mirrors how quoted-token excludes DQUOTE below, just
                ; extended to a two-character delimiter. The trailing *"*"
                ; matters: without it, a body of a single bare "*" (e.g.
                ; "/***/") has nowhere to go, since every star would
                ; otherwise be forced to pair with a following character.
non-star      = %x00-29 / %x2B-10FFFF   ; any octet other than '*' (0x2A)
not-slash     = %x00-2E / %x30-10FFFF   ; any octet other than '/' (0x2F)

token         = quoted-token / bare-token
quoted-token  = DQUOTE *(%x00-21 / %x23-10FFFF) [DQUOTE]
                ; contents are copied verbatim, no escape handling; an
                ; unterminated quote runs to end of file
bare-token    = 1*(%x21-10FFFF)
                ; any run of bytes above 0x20 (space); comments are only
                ; recognized where a *new* token would start, so a bare
                ; token can itself contain "//", "/*", or '"' after its
                ; first character

integer       = ["-"] 1*DIGIT
                ; parsed with atoi: only the leading run of digits matters;
                ; anything after the first non-digit character is ignored
                ; rather than rejected
number        = ["-"] (1*DIGIT ["." *DIGIT] / "." 1*DIGIT)
                ; parsed with atof; same "trailing junk is ignored, not
                ; rejected" note as integer

; === animation.cfg ===
;
; BG_ParseAnimationFile: an unconditional stream of 5-token records. Order
; doesn't matter and there's no block structure. anim-name is looked up
; against a built-in animation-name table at runtime, but that lookup has
; no bearing on the file's syntax - an unrecognized name is still an
; ordinary, valid anim-name token, carried through as-is.

animation-cfg-file = *sep *(anim-entry *sep)
anim-entry         = anim-name sep first-frame sep num-frames sep loop-frames sep fps

anim-name          = token
first-frame        = integer
num-frames         = integer
loop-frames        = integer
fps                = number
                     ; negative means "play backwards"; 0 is treated as 1

; === animevents.cfg ===
;
; BG_ParseAnimationEvtFile + ParseAnimationEvtBlock. Top level is a
; sequence of directives; as with anim-name above, any keyword-driven
; branch that doesn't match a known keyword is a normal (bounded)
; alternative here, not an error condition.

animevents-cfg-file = *sep *(directive *sep)

directive          = include-directive / events-block / stray-directive
stray-directive    = token
                     ; anything other than "include"/"UPPEREVENTS"/
                     ; "LOWEREVENTS" - this token is simply consumed as its
                     ; own (inert) directive

include-directive  = "include" sep include-path
include-path       = token
                     ; a player-model directory name; the loader appends it
                     ; between "models/players/" and "/animevents.cfg" to
                     ; find the included file, which is itself a complete
                     ; file of this same animevents-cfg-file grammar

events-block       = block-keyword sep *(token sep) "{" sep *(event-entry sep) "}"
                     ; the *(token sep) mirrors the real parser: it skips
                     ; forward over anything at all in search of the next
                     ; "{", rather than requiring the block body to open
                     ; immediately
block-keyword      = "UPPEREVENTS" / "LOWEREVENTS"

event-entry        = anim-name sep entry-body
entry-body         = known-args-entry / bare-entry
known-args-entry   = event-type sep frame-offset sep event-args
bare-entry         = token
                     ; event-type didn't match one of the six keywords
                     ; below - this also covers AEV_SABER_SWING and
                     ; AEV_SABER_SPIN, which are recognized *names* (present
                     ; in the lookup table) but have no argument case in
                     ; the source; writing one directly is a no-op. They're
                     ; normally produced indirectly, when an AEV_SOUND
                     ; entry's sound-path matches a magic saber-sound
                     ; prefix (see sound-path below), not written directly.
                     ; Either way, no further tokens belong to this entry -
                     ; the next token starts a fresh anim-name attempt.

frame-offset       = integer
                     ; added to this anim's first-frame from animation.cfg

event-type         = "AEV_SOUND" / "AEV_SOUNDCHAN" / "AEV_FOOTSTEP"
                   / "AEV_EFFECT" / "AEV_FIRE" / "AEV_MOVE"

event-args         = sound-args / soundchan-args / footstep-args
                   / effect-args / fire-args / move-args
                     ; which alternative applies is determined by the
                     ; event-type that preceded it, not by the shape of the
                     ; arguments themselves

sound-args         = sound-path sep random-low sep random-high sep chance
soundchan-args     = channel sep sound-path sep random-low sep random-high sep chance
footstep-args      = footstep-type sep chance
effect-args        = effect-path sep bolt-name sep chance
fire-args          = alt-fire sep chance
move-args          = forward-push sep right-push sep up-push

sound-path         = token
                     ; e.g. "sound/chars/kyle/misc/pain1.mp3". A "%d"-style
                     ; sprintf placeholder combined with random-low/
                     ; random-high > 0 picks a random numbered variant
                     ; instead of one fixed file. A leading "*" marks a
                     ; custom/dynamic sound (not looked up as a file). If
                     ; this path matches a built-in saber-sound prefix
                     ; ("sound/weapons/saber/saberhup..." or
                     ; "...saberspin..."), the engine silently reclassifies
                     ; the whole entry as AEV_SABER_SWING/AEV_SABER_SPIN at
                     ; runtime - a semantic effect, not a syntax one.
random-low         = integer
random-high        = integer
chance             = integer
                     ; a percentage by convention; not range-checked

channel            = "CHAN_VOICE_ATTEN" / "CHAN_VOICE_GLOBAL" / "CHAN_ANNOUNCER"
                   / "CHAN_BODY" / "CHAN_WEAPON" / "CHAN_VOICE" / token
                     ; any value other than the six listed silently
                     ; defaults to CHAN_AUTO at runtime

footstep-type      = "FOOTSTEP_R" / "FOOTSTEP_L" / "FOOTSTEP_HEAVY_R" / "FOOTSTEP_HEAVY_L" / token
                     ; unlike channel, an unrecognized value has no default -
                     ; it's simply stored as an unmatched index at runtime

effect-path        = token

bolt-name          = "none" / "NULL" / token
                     ; "none"/"NULL" mean "no bolt"; anything else is used
                     ; as a literal bolt-tag name

alt-fire           = integer
forward-push       = integer
right-push         = integer
up-push            = integer
